{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775874897388,"sessionID":"ses_2859c19c1ffeZ9El7LkVpI02HE","part":{"id":"prt_d7a6471b4001jFXOj25HyblYBD","messageID":"msg_d7a646a630018jtArLZltGqEs4","sessionID":"ses_2859c19c1ffeZ9El7LkVpI02HE","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_b426e93e336d416c8b7423e6","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-032/proposal.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-032/proposal.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AR-032: Dockerfile 多阶段构建 (3 images)\n2: \n3: ## Summary\n4: \n5: Implement multi-stage Docker builds for AgentCube server components, consolidating from multiple separate Dockerfiles into 3 optimized container images: `agentcube-router`, `agentcube-workload-manager`, and `agentcube-agentd` (with `picod` sidecar option).\n6: \n7: ## Purpose\n8: \n9: ### Background\n10: \n11: AgentCube currently lacks a unified Docker build strategy for its server-side Go binaries. The project has 4 binaries that need to be containerized:\n12: - `router` — HTTP traffic router with session management\n13: - `workload-manager` — Sandbox orchestration controller\n14: - `agentd` — Idle cleanup controller\n15: - `picod` — Daemon for sandbox pods (sidecar pattern)\n16: \n17: Without multi-stage builds, each component requires separate build contexts, large base images, and manual artifact management. This increases CI/CD complexity and image size.\n18: \n19: ### Goal\n20: \n21: Create consolidated Dockerfiles using multi-stage builds at `docker/`:\n22: - Consolidate build artifacts into minimal runtime images\n23: - Reduce image size by ~60-70% compared to single-stage builds\n24: - Use distroless or Alpine base images for production\n25: - Support both development (with debugging tools) and production builds\n26: \n27: ### Value\n28: \n29: - **Image Size**: Smaller images (~50-100MB vs ~300MB+)\n30: - **Security**: Fewer packages in runtime image = smaller attack surface\n31: - **Build Speed**: Cached build stages speed up CI/CD\n32: - **Maintainability**: Single Dockerfile pattern per image type\n33: - **Consistency**: Unified build pipeline across all components\n34: \n35: ---\n36: \n37: ## Scope\n38: \n39: ### In-Scope\n40: \n41: | Component | Path | Description |\n42: |-----------|------|-------------|\n43: | Router Dockerfile | `docker/Dockerfile.router` | Multi-stage build for router binary |\n44: | Workload Manager Dockerfile | `docker/Dockerfile.workload-manager` | Multi-stage build for workload-manager binary |\n45: | Agentd Dockerfile | `docker/Dockerfile.agentd` | Multi-stage build for agentd binary (includes picod option) |\n46: | Base build stage | `docker/base.Dockerfile` | Shared Go build environment |\n47: | Makefile targets | `Makefile` | Build commands for all images |\n48: \n49: ### Out-of-Scope\n50: \n51: - Agent workspace Dockerfiles (already exists in `agentcube/services/docker_service.py`)\n52: - Helm chart image references (covered by AR-030)\n53: - Multi-arch image manifests (amd64/arm64)\n54: - Image registry push pipeline\n55: - Local development docker-compose setup\n56: \n57: ---\n58: \n59: ## Impact Analysis\n60: \n61: ### Dependencies\n62: \n63: | Dependency | Purpose | Status |\n64: |------------|---------|--------|\n65: | Go 1.24+ | Build toolchain for server binaries | Already in go.mod |\n66: | Docker/Make | Image build execution | Required |\n67: | Alpine Linux | Runtime base image | Required |\n68: | distroless/static | Optional minimal base | Optional |\n69: \n70: ### Upstream\n71: \n72: - `cmd/router/` — Router source code\n73: - `cmd/workload-manager/` — Workload Manager source code\n74: - `cmd/agentd/` — Agentd source code\n75: - `cmd/picod/` — Picod source code\n76: - `go.mod` / `go.sum` — Go dependencies\n77: \n78: ### Downstream Consumers\n79: \n80: 1. **CI/CD pipelines** — Build and push images to registry\n81: 2. **Helm chart (AR-030)** — References image tags\n82: 3. **E2E tests** — Deploy images to test cluster\n83: 4. **Operators** — Pull images for production deployment\n84: \n85: ### Risks\n86: \n87: | Risk | Severity | Mitigation |\n88: |------|----------|------------|\n89: | Build cache invalidation | Medium | Structure stages to maximize cache reuse |\n90: | Binary size regression | Medium | Add size checks in Makefile |\n91: | Missing build args | Low | Document required --build-arg values |\n92: | Cross-platform builds | Low | Use --platform for multi-arch support |\n93: \n94: ---\n95: \n96: ## Alternatives Considered\n97: \n98: ### Option 1: Single monolithic image (Not Selected)\n99: \n100: **Pros**: Simple single image to manage\n101: **Cons**: Bloated image, all components run even if unused, security risk, slower deployments\n102: \n103: ### Option 2: Separate Dockerfiles per binary (Not Selected)\n104: \n105: **Pros**: Maximum flexibility, no shared stages\n106: **Cons**: Duplicated build logic, harder to maintain, no cache sharing\n107: \n108: ### Option 3: Multi-stage with shared build stage (Selected)\n109: \n110: **Pros**: Optimized image size, shared Go toolchain cache, maintainable, follows best practices\n111: **Cons**: More complex initial setup, requires understanding of multi-stage builds\n112: \n113: ### Option 4: Distroless images (Not Selected for initial)\n114: \n115: **Pros**: Minimal possible size, highest security\n116: **Cons**: Debugging difficult, requires additional tooling for production support\n117: \n118: ---\n119: \n120: ## Technical Design\n121: \n122: ### Image Structure\n123: \n124: ```\n125: docker/\n126: ├── base.Dockerfile          # Shared Go build stage (builder)\n127: ├── Dockerfile.router        # Router: builder → alpine runtime\n128: ├── Dockerfile.workload-manager  # Workload Manager: builder → alpine runtime\n129: └── Dockerfile.agentd        # Agentd + Picod: builder → alpine runtime\n130: ```\n131: \n132: ### Build Stage Pattern\n133: \n134: Each runtime Dockerfile follows this pattern:\n135: \n136: ```dockerfile\n137: # Stage 1: Builder\n138: FROM golang:1.24-alpine AS builder\n139: WORKDIR /build\n140: COPY go.mod go.sum ./\n141: RUN go mod download\n142: COPY . .\n143: RUN CGO_ENABLED=0 GOOS=linux go build -o /bin/[binary] ./cmd/[binary]\n144: \n145: # Stage 2: Runtime\n146: FROM alpine:3.19 AS runtime\n147: RUN adduser -D -u 1000 agentcube\n148: USER 1000\n149: COPY --from=builder /bin/[binary] /usr/local/bin/\n150: ENTRYPOINT [\"/usr/local/bin/[binary]\"]\n151: ```\n152: \n153: ### Image Targets\n154: \n155: | Image | Binary | Base Image | Expected Size |\n156: |-------|--------|------------|---------------|\n157: | agentcube-router | router | alpine:3.19 | ~25-30MB |\n158: | agentcube-workload-manager | workload-manager | alpine:3.19 | ~30-35MB |\n159: | agentcube-agentd | agentd + picod | alpine:3.19 | ~35-40MB |\n160: \n161: ### Makefile Targets\n162: \n163: ```makefile\n164: .PHONY: docker-build docker-push docker-buildx\n165: \n166: docker-build: docker-build-router docker-build-workload-manager docker-build-agentd\n167: \n168: docker-build-router:\n169: \tdocker build -f docker/Dockerfile.router -t agentcube-router:latest .\n170: \n171: docker-build-workload-manager:\n172: \tdocker build -f docker/Dockerfile.workload-manager -t agentcube-workload-manager:latest .\n173: \n174: docker-build-agentd:\n175: \tdocker build -f docker/Dockerfile.agentd -t agentcube-agentd:latest .\n176: \n177: docker-push: docker-build\n178: \tdocker push agentcube-router:latest\n179: \tdocker push agentcube-workload-manager:latest\n180: \tdocker push agentcube-agentd:latest\n181: ```\n182: \n183: ### Build Args\n184: \n185: | Arg | Default | Purpose |\n186: |-----|---------|---------|\n187: | GO_VERSION | 1.24 | Go toolchain version |\n188: | BUILDER_IMAGE | golang:1.24-alpine | Build stage base |\n189: | RUNTIME_IMAGE | alpine:3.19 | Runtime stage base |\n190: | BINARY_VERSION | dev | Binary version info |\n191: \n192: ---\n193: \n194: ## Implementation Plan\n195: \n196: ### Phase 1: Create directory structure\n197: \n198: - [ ] Create `docker/` directory\n199: - [ ] Create `docker/base.Dockerfile` for shared Go build environment\n200: \n201: ### Phase 2: Implement Router Dockerfile\n202: \n203: - [ ] Create `docker/Dockerfile.router` with multi-stage build\n204: - [ ] Add health check endpoint configuration\n205: - [ ] Test build locally\n206: \n207: ### Phase 3: Implement Workload Manager Dockerfile\n208: \n209: - [ ] Create `docker/Dockerfile.workload-manager`\n210: - [ ] Configure Redis connection via env vars\n211: - [ ] Test build locally\n212: \n213: ### Phase 4: Implement Agentd Dockerfile\n214: \n215: - [ ] Create `docker/Dockerfile.agentd`\n216: - [ ] Include picod as secondary binary or sidecar\n217: - [ ] Test build locally\n218: \n219: ### Phase 5: Add Makefile targets\n220: \n221: - [ ] Add `docker-build-*` targets to Makefile\n222: - [ ] Add `docker-push` target\n223: - [ ] Add size validation target\n224: \n225: ### Phase 6: CI integration\n226: \n227: - [ ] Add GitHub Actions workflow for docker build/push\n228: - [ ] Add image size checks to CI\n229: - [ ] Configure buildx for multi-arch (future)\n230: \n231: ---\n232: \n233: ## Acceptance Criteria\n234: \n235: | ID | Scenario | Expected Result |\n236: |----|----------|-----------------|\n237: | DOCKER-001 | Build router image | `docker build -f docker/Dockerfile.router` succeeds, image ~25-30MB |\n238: | DOCKER-002 | Build workload-manager image | Image builds successfully, ~30-35MB |\n239: | DOCKER-003 | Build agentd image | Image builds successfully, includes agentd and picod, ~35-40MB |\n240: | DOCKER-004 | Verify binary executes | `docker run --rm agentcube-router version` outputs version |\n241: | DOCKER-005 | Verify non-root user | Running container uses non-root UID (1000) |\n242: | DOCKER-006 | Multi-stage layers present | `docker history` shows builder and runtime stages |\n243: | DOCKER-007 | Makefile targets work | `make docker-build` builds all 3 images |\n244: | DOCKER-008 | Cache reuse | Rebuild with no code changes uses cached stages |\n245: \n246: ---\n247: \n248: ## Timeline Estimate\n249: \n250: | Phase | Effort |\n251: |-------|--------|\n252: | Directory structure | 30 minutes |\n253: | Router Dockerfile | 1 hour |\n254: | Workload Manager Dockerfile | 1 hour |\n255: | Agentd Dockerfile | 1 hour |\n256: | Makefile integration | 30 minutes |\n257: | CI integration | 1 hour |\n258: | Testing & validation | 1 hour |\n259: | **Total** | **6 hours** |\n260: \n261: ---\n262: \n263: ## Relationship to Other ARs\n264: \n265: - **AR-030** — Helm chart references these images; update values.yaml after image naming finalized\n266: - **AR-031** — RBAC manifests need to reference ServiceAccount names used in images\n267: - **AR-024** — DockerService.build_image() used for agent workspace builds, not affected\n\n(End of file - total 267 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AR-032: Dockerfile 多阶段构建 (3 images)\n\n## Summary\n\nImplement multi-stage Docker builds for AgentCube server components, consolidating from multiple separate Dockerfiles into 3 optimized container images: `agentcube-router`, `agentcube-workload-manager`, and `agentcube-agentd` (with `picod` sidecar option).\n\n## Purpose\n\n### Background\n\nAgentCube currently lacks a unified Docker build strategy for its server-side Go binaries. The project has 4 binaries that need to be containerized:\n- `router` — HTTP traffic router with session management\n- `workload-manager` — Sandbox orchestration controller\n- `agentd` — Idle cleanup controller\n- `picod` — Daemon for sandbox pods (sidecar pattern)\n\nWithout multi-stage builds, each component requires separate build contexts, large base images, and manual artifact management. This increases CI/CD complexity and image size.\n\n### Goal\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-032/proposal.md","time":{"start":1775874897370,"end":1775874897386}}}}
